I’d only met @andrewshepard’s Grandma Judy in person once when we started exchanging letters between Hong Kong and Michigan. I included notes from Judy in the mix of documents I brought to interview for my ~fiancé~ visa. What better proof than a grandmother’s approval?

Judy adored Shakespeare and chai lattes. She baked the world’s best pies. She worked as a book conservator for the New York Botanical Garden and loved going for Italian food on Arthur Avenue. She didn’t understand why some of her neighbors in Westchester wouldn’t go into the city in the 1970s. (“It was right there!” she’d say with wide eyes, shaking her head.)

Judy spent part of her youth in Panama, where her father worked during WWII. But her heart belongs in the Upper Peninsula of Michigan. Her Finnish family bought property on Stanley Lake in the 1940s and built their sauna first. If you told her someone didn’t appreciate sauna, she’d raise her eyebrows.

Judy married John more than six decades ago. They’ve done everything together since, road-tripping across the U.S. and beyond. (Here, dancing in St. Louis in 2015.) In their house happy hour is at 5 p.m. sharp.

Please have a little happy hour in celebration of GMa Judy one evening this week. ❤️

~11 days into January and I’m already behind on my resolution to clean up my camera roll (and drop it here) now and then. Onward!

❄️ Ice dips, a better view than mine, Alex Katz, *the* crossword, mountain dood, Chet’s, cheese for dinner, parking lot heels and the first sunset of 2023.

Book club in the woods and a mountaintop covered in hoarfrost. (Twice, because it’s just that dreary in New York today.)

From NYT, 1958: “This is the season when hoarfrost comes in the night to make magic of the commonplace. Walk abroad before the sun has risen more than a hand's breadth, and if the night has been seasonal there is a crisp white filigree on grass blade, weed stem and withered leaf, a tracery of crystal that came in the damp, cold darkness and will vanish in the first warmth of daylight.”
Late January: Disco balls for chilly days, “pink-a-boo pineberries” and false teeth on Flatbush 🪩🕺🏼

Recently ⚡️ Llamas and curiosities at the @eamesinstitute, hikes in cold rain and crisp snow, gaudy birthday décor, and the single rose our local florist offered @andrewshepard when he tried to buy flowers on the 14th. (Loved it.)
Honolulu, fueled by caffeine (not pictured), shave ice (not pictured) and salt water (kind of pictured) 🌺🪷
Took a submarine down to see an artificial reef for @jimmac3066’s birthday. For the record, the only shark we spotted was sound asleep. 🦈💤
🌋 Big Island: Lava Cats, The Musical 🎶
Digging through the Maui archives, slowly but surely, and dreaming of shave ice. 🤿🌴
April: Gardens and allergies -> nasal rinse and repeat 🌸

May (🫣😅) kicked off with my second round of covid and ended with a big birthday gathering for @andrewshepard. 

Is 2023 moving along at a really bizarre pace? Just me?
June: Beach hunting in the Bahamas, butterflies and babies, Trudy in her wedding look, the dream piano (free! on wheels!), two of @meghan_petersen’s 40 miles and … wildfire skies.

Four perfect days celebrating Felicia + Max. ❤️ I am guaranteed to tear up at your wedding, and @andrewshepard is guaranteed to tear up the dance floor. (Neither of these things is pictured here.)

📸 #5 by @kdombsadof 🧜‍♀️
Seven hours hiking/wading/swimming/scrambling through the Narrows — or, How We Discovered Several Muscles We Didn’t Know Existed 😅 @zionnps
Still swooning over these views — and this day in general.

I forgot to document most of the things we did and people we saw in Canada this Christmas. (Cold hands, rainy days, too busy laughing etc.) No regrets.
